{{date|February 29, 2016}}{{Film}}
Yesterday [[Leonardo DiCaprio]] won his first Oscar, for {{w|Academy Award for Best Actor|Best Actor}}, at the 88th {{w|Academy Awards}}. The award ended DiCaprio's long wait for an Academy Award &mdash; he was first nominated in 1993 and won on his sixth nomination, for his role in ''{{w|The Revenant (2015 film)|The Revenant}}'', which also won Best Cinematography and Best Director.
[[File:Leonardo DiCaprio 2014.jpg|left|thumb|File photo of DiCaprio{{image|Christopher William Adach}}]]{{QuoteRight|I thank you all for this amazing award tonight. Let us not take this planet for granted. I do not take tonight for granted. Thank you so very much.|source=Leonardo DiCaprio}}
In his acceptance speech, DiCaprio described ''The Revenant'' as "about man's relationship to the natural world", and spoke of underprivileged people affected adversely by human activities on nature. He also said "Our production needed to move to the southern tip of this planet just to be able to find snow". He concluded saying "I thank you all for this amazing award tonight. Let us not take this planet for granted. I do not take tonight for granted. Thank you so very much."

DiCaprio was previously nominated for his work in ''{{w|The Wolf of Wall Street (2013 film)|The Wolf of Wall Street}}'', for Best Actor and Best Picture; ''{{w|Blood Diamond (film)|Blood Diamond}}'', for Best Actor; ''{{w|The Aviator (2004 film)|The Aviator}}'', Best Actor; and ''{{w|What's Eating Gilbert Grape}}'', for Best Supporting Actor.

{{w|Kate Winslet}}, who co-starred with DiCaprio in ''{{w|Titanic (1997 film)|Titanic}}'', was nominated for {{w|Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress}} for ''{{w|Steve Jobs (2015 film)|Steve Jobs}}'', but lost to [[Sweden|Swedish]] actress {{w|Alicia Vikander}} for her role in ''{{w|The Danish Girl (film)|The Danish Girl}}''.  {{w|Brie Larson}} collected Best Actress for her performance in ''{{w|Room (2015 film)|Room}}''.

''{{w|Mad Max: Fury Road}}'' had ten nominations and won six of them: Best Costume Design, Film Editing, Makeup and Hairstyling, Production Design, Sound Editing, and Sound Mixing. ''{{w|Ex Machina (film)|Ex Machina}}'' won the award for Best Visual Effects. ''{{w|Spotlight (film)|Spotlight}}'' won the Best Picture award, and {{w|Sam Smith (singer)|Sam Smith}}'s song ''{{w|Writing's on the Wall (Sam Smith song)|Writing's on the Wall}}'' won Best Original Song for ''{{w|Spectre (2015 film)|Spectre}}'' ahead of the Grammy-winning song ''{{w|Earned It}}'' by [[Canada|Canadian]] singer {{w|The Weeknd}}.

